VOT_REAS_FOR_Text: One thing that seems to have been lacking in this survey is the perspectives of the indigenous peoples who have lived in what is currently called the state of Colorado for far longer than the state has existed. I think that the reintroduction of wolves to Colorado can also be important to the concept of Land Back, especially if such work is led by Indigenous knowledge of living with the land, rather than against it.

VOT_REAS_AG_Text: Special fencing, guard dogs and personnel to manage wolves in CO cost money the state could spend in better ways.  People who live in the urban areas don't ever have to worry about wolves whereas everyone else, especially ranchers, do.  Hunting animals that the wolves kill (and sometimes do not fully eat) is also extremely important for wilflife mgmt and bringing hunter dollars to the CPW and state tourism.  Wolves become essentially a competitor for what hunters are trying to kill for meat/animal mgmt.

VOT_REAS_AG_Text: The consequences of reintroducing the wolf are unknown, and dealing with wolves is something Coloradoans haven't dealt with in generations.  In addition, generations of families have structured their lives around existing conditions, which doesn't include wolves.  It was wrong to kill off the wolves a century ago, but it's just as wrong to reintroduce them forcefully now.  Let them come on their own, in due time.  As (if) they do, we can slowly learn to live with them again.
